<DOC><DOCNO>WSJ910318-0050</DOCNO><DOCID>910318-0050.</DOCID><HL>   Law:   Xerox Settles Age-Bias Suit   Brought by Ex-Employees</HL><DATE>02/27/91</DATE><SO>WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), NO PAGE CITATION</SO><CO>   XRX LABOR</CO><IN>OFFICE EQUIPMENT (OFF)</IN><LP>   STAMFORD, Conn. -- Xerox Corp. said it settled a lawsuitbrought by 13 former employees who had charged theoffice-equipment company with age discrimination.   Neither Xerox nor an attorney for the former employeeswould disclose details of the settlement, except to say thatall individual claims in the case, filed in federal court in1983, have been dismissed. Xerox said the settlement won'thave any effect on its financial statements and reiteratedits denial of any wrongdoing.</LP><TEXT>   Robert Joffe, of Joffe andamp; Schlesinger, one of several lawfirms representing the former Xerox employees, said heintended to file a motion asking the court to recertify thecase as a class action. A class was conditionally certifiedin the case in 1984, drawing more than 1,300 potentialcomplainants, but it was decertified three years later.   Xerox said the 13 former employees relinquished any rightto an award in a class-action suit; Mr. Joffe declined tocomment on the settlement, citing a confidentiality order.About 20 other former Xerox employees have filed individuallawsuits against Xerox, which said it will continue to fightthem.   A Xerox spokesman said none of the former employees werereinstated as a result of the settlement.</TEXT></DOC>